Introduction¶

Dataset Description¶

In this report we provide an analysis on The Movie Database (TMDb), which contains information about 10,000 movies, released during the period between 1960-2015 years. The dataset contains information valuable for the decision making in relation to the movie production, such as:

  • underlying details of a movie (title, genre, director, cast, production company, tagline, keywords, homepage and overview);
  • economics: budget and revenue in nominal and real terms (adjusted for inflation, in 2010 US $);
  • popularity, average user rating and count;
  • duration and release period.

For more details of a dataset, please refer to the section below.

Based on the description of numerical columns and histograms presented below, the following observations have been made:

OBSERVATION 1. Popularity column seems to have outliers in dataset, where mean and 25-75 percentiles are in a range of 0-1 and max value goes up to 32.99 points. Below histogram for popularity as well shows skewness to the left of the majority of values, indicating for the existence of outliers, which potentially can be investigated in a separate analysis.

OBSERVATION 2. Budget, revenue and their adjusted versions have a significant portion of zero values. For the purpose of this analysis, we assume that the dataset in this regard is correct and zero values represent unsuccessful releases with no budget, thus avoiding cleaning dataset removing zero line items in this case.

OBSERVATION 3. Runtime has a mean of 102 and median of 99, indicating that there is a certain movie runtime standard in the industry. However, as there are still 247 unique values in the runtime field, for the purpose of our analysis we have decided to use additionally 3 categories of movies based on runtime statistics, grouping as per below:

      >> Short   <= 90 min ; Medium  > 90 and <= 111 min ; Long    > 111 min

OBSERVATION 4. Following the description of Vote average, we can assume that User rating is between 0-10, where 10 has the maximum value.

OBSERVATION 5. Although database contains information for more than 50 years, the later years has increasing number of movies compared to the earlier periods (that can be seen in the histogram below for Release year). Meaning that our analysis will be impacted by the increased number of movies produced overtime, esp. in the later periods

# Generating a function to plot histograms for the selected columns in the dataset
def generate_histogram(df, column_name, bins=10, title='Histogram', xlabel='Values', ylabel='Frequency'):
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    plt.hist(df[column_name], bins=bins, color='blue', alpha=0.7, edgecolor='black')
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.grid(axis='y', alpha=0.75)
    plt.show()

Questions for Analysis¶

Our analysis and hence the report will be focused on the financial and economical aspects of a movie production, specifically what correlates with high revenues (budget, popularity, user rating and/or runtime) and what are the characteristics of a high ROI (Return on Investment) movie.

Question #1. What correlates with revenues the most: budgets, popularity, user rating or runtime?

Question #2. What are the characteristics of a high ROI movie (from the financial point of view)?

where ROI (Return on Investment) is Revenue / Budget (both adjusted for inflation)

Specifically:
  • which genres have high ROI;
  • what is the best runtime (range) of movies with the highest ROI;
  • which release months of a year have the highest ROI;
  • whether ROI changed overtime or it's rather stable in relation to a release year.

We have decided to analyse ROI (compared to Revenue only), as high revenues not always ensure a financial success of a movie.

Data Wrangling¶

Data Cleaning¶

I. Release date column conversion to a correct Date Type format, required for further processing of a release date and months during EDA steps below.

Following NOTE 1 in Dataset Description section above, we have converted data type of a Release date to a Date format from Object.

We will perform this conversion in two steps:

  1. convert to a correct data type;
  2. use Release year column to extract a year and append it to date and month from the Release date column - This is needed to ensure correct interpretation of a year column, e.g. 1972 vs 2072 for 72 as an example.
In [16]:
# Step 1. Correcting data type
df['release_date'] = pd.to_datetime(df['release_date'], format='%m/%d/%y')

# Step 2. Appending Release date to Release year to ensure correct intepretation of a year column
df['release_date'] = pd.to_datetime(
    df['release_date'].dt.strftime('%m-%d') + '-' + df['release_year'].astype(str),
    format='%m-%d-%Y'
)

III. Transforming Genres data. During EDA process we are planning to use Genres for our analysis, specifically in calculation of ROI per genre. However, data on Genres is stored in one column and this column contains several values, separated by "|", which needs to be transformed. Please follow below commented steps to get insights into the logic of the transformation.

Result. 20 unique Genres, each in a separate column with binary values (0 - no, 1 -yes)

LIMITATION. Each movie can be in several genres, which means that the total count of all the genres will be higher than the total number of movies. Subsequently, there is duplicated statistics in those cases.

In [19]:
# Transforming the 'genres' column into separate binary columns
genre_dummies = df['genres'].str.get_dummies(sep='|')

# Adding prefix 'Genre_' to each of the new genre columns to easier separate them from the rest of the columns
genre_dummies = genre_dummies.add_prefix('Genre_')

# Concatenate the original DataFrame with the new genre columns
df = pd.concat([df, genre_dummies], axis=1)

In [21]:
# Define a function to categorize years into custom ranges
def categorize_year(year):
    if year < 1975:
        return '1960-1974'
    elif year < 1990:
        return '1975-1989'
    elif year < 2000:
        return '1990-1999'
    elif year < 2010:
        return '2000-2009'
    else:
        return '2010-2015'

# Apply the function to create a new column 'year_range'
df['year_range'] = df['release_year'].apply(categorize_year)

# Sort the DataFrame by year ranges from latest to oldest
year_order = ['2010-2015', '2000-2009', '1990-1999', '1975-1989', '1960-1974']
df['year_range'] = pd.Categorical(df['year_range'], categories=year_order, ordered=True)
df = df.sort_values('year_range')

def plot_scatter_by_variable(df, variable):
    # Creating scatter plots for each year range
    year_ranges = df['year_range'].unique()

    # Create a figure with subplots for each year range, using a grid layout
    ncols = 2  # Number of columns
    nrows = (len(year_ranges) + ncols - 1) // ncols  # Calculate number of rows needed
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(nrows=nrows, ncols=ncols, figsize=(12, 5 * nrows))
    # Flatten axes array if necessary
    axes = axes.flatten()

    # Create a scatter plot
    for ax, year_range in zip(axes, year_ranges):
        # Filter the DataFrame for the current year range
        range_data = df[df['year_range'] == year_range]

        # Create the scatter plot for the current year range
        ax.scatter(range_data[variable], range_data['revenue_adj'], alpha=0.5, label='Data Points')

        # Fit a linear regression line
        if len(range_data) > 1:  # Ensure there are enough points to fit a line
            # Calculate the linear regression line
            slope, intercept = np.polyfit(range_data[variable], range_data['revenue_adj'], 1)
            x_vals = np.array(range_data[variable])
            y_vals = slope * x_vals + intercept
            ax.plot(x_vals, y_vals, color='red', label='Regression Line')

        # Adding labels and title for each subplot
        ax.set_title(f'Scatter Plot of Adj Revenue vs {variable.capitalize()} for {year_range}', fontsize=12)
        ax.set_xlabel(variable.capitalize(), fontsize=10)
        ax.set_ylabel('Adjusted Revenue', fontsize=10)
        ax.grid()
        ax.legend()

    # Hide any unused subplots
    for i in range(len(year_ranges), len(axes)):
        fig.delaxes(axes[i])
    plt.tight_layout()

    # Show the plot
    plt.show()

III. In order to quantify the relationship between Revenue and Budget, let's calculate the correlation coefficient using the same year categories

In [23]:
def calculate_correlation(df, variable):
    # Group by 'year_range' and calculate the correlation coefficient
    correlation_results = df.groupby('year_range', observed=True).agg(
        correlation_coefficient=('revenue_adj', lambda x: x.corr(df.loc[x.index, variable]))
    )

    # Convert results to a DataFrame for better readability
    correlation_df = correlation_results.reset_index()

    return correlation_df

Research Question 2 What are the characteristics of a high ROI movie (from the financial point of view)?¶

where ROI (Return on Investment) = Revenue / Budget (both adjusted for inflation)

Specifically:
  • which genres have high ROI;
  • what is the best runtime (range) of movies with the highest ROI;
  • which release months of a year have high ROI;
  • whether ROI changed overtime or it's rather stable in relation to a release year.

In order to calculate ROI, in the below analysis we used two different approaches:

  1. via calculating Total ROI per genre, e.g. summing Total Revenue generated for all the movies in scope divided by (/) the Total Budget Spend for all the movies in scope. If we assume that the movies in scope represent a movie production industry, then we calculate what will be ROI of a movie production industry as a whole, without considering ROI per movie.
  2. ROI per movie

Resulting Total ROI (I) and ROI per movie (II) calculations give a different perspective on the analysis from the financial point of view.

I. In the below calculations we derive Total ROI for the movies in scope, per genre, without considering ROI per movie to get an overview of Revenue / Budget ratio for the aggregated amounts.

In [34]:
# Creating a DataFrame to hold the ROI per genre
genre_columns = [col for col in df.columns if col.startswith('Genre_')]
roi_per_genre = {}

# Calculate ROI, average revenue, and average budget per genre
for genre in genre_columns:
    # Filter the DataFrame for the current genre
    genre_data = df[df[genre] == 1]
    
    # Calculate sums for revenue and budget for the genre
    total_revenue = genre_data['revenue_adj'].sum()
    total_budget = genre_data['budget_adj'].sum()
    
    # Calculate averages for revenue and budget (we decided to show in mln of USD for a better readability)
    average_revenue_mln = genre_data['revenue_adj'].mean() / 1000000
    average_budget_mln = genre_data['budget_adj'].mean() / 1000000
    
    # Calculate ROI, handling division by zero
    roi = total_revenue / total_budget if total_budget > 0 else 0
    
    # Count the number of films in the genre
    genre_count = genre_data.shape[0]
    
    # Store the results in a dictionary
    roi_per_genre[genre] = {
        'Total ROI': roi,
        'AVG Revenue, mln $': average_revenue_mln,
        'AVG Budget, mln $': average_budget_mln,
        'Genre Count': genre_count
    }

# Convert the results to a DataFrame for better readability
roi_per_genre_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(roi_per_genre, orient='index').reset_index()
roi_per_genre_df.columns = ['Genre', 'Total ROI', 'AVG Revenue mln$', 'AVG Budget mln$', 'Count']

# Sort the DataFrame by Total ROI in descending order
roi_per_genre_df = roi_per_genre_df.sort_values(by='Total ROI', ascending=False)

# Display the sorted total ROI per genre with averages and genre count
print(roi_per_genre_df)

Insight #5. Counting a full Budget Spend vs Revenue Generated for all the movies in scope as a total, Documentary genre has the highest Total ROI, mainly driven by one of the lowest Budget spends on Average compared to other genres. Documentary genre stands-out from the other leading genres: although it has the highest Total ROI, Average Revenue generated is rather low. Meaning that if we want to go with maximizing ROI only we could consider Documentary genre, however it has certain limitations in terms upward potential of Revenue. An investor with limited financial resources could consider focusing in this genre.

Genres Music and Animation are the next top 3, where Animation requires more than double Spending while generates higher revenues compared to Music.

Genre Family has similar picture to Animation, but we observe higher number of movies as a count, indicating the bigger size of the market in general of that segment.

Genre Adventure has the highest Average Budget Spend across the board as well as Average Revenue, although generating high Total ROI as top 5, meaning that this segment could be of a good consideration of an investor with unrestricted financial resources.

Genre Horror stands out by rather a low Average budget spend, compared to the majority of other genres.

In [39]:
# Creating a function, which calculates Total ROI per Runtime group, release year and release month.
def calculate_roi_per_category(df, category_column):
    # Create a DataFrame to hold the ROI per category
    roi_per_category = {}

    # Group by the specified category column
    grouped_data = df.groupby(category_column, observed=True)

    # Calculate ROI, average revenue, and average budget per category
    for category, group in grouped_data:
        # Calculate sums for revenue and budget for the category
        total_revenue = group['revenue_adj'].sum()
        total_budget = group['budget_adj'].sum()

        # Calculate averages for revenue and budget, we have decided to calculate in mln of USD for a better readability
        average_revenue_mln = group['revenue_adj'].mean() / 1000000
        average_budget_mln = group['budget_adj'].mean() / 1000000

        # Calculate ROI, handling division by zero
        roi = total_revenue / total_budget if total_budget > 0 else 0

        # Count the number of films in the category
        category_count = group.shape[0]

        # Store the results in a dictionary
        roi_per_category[category] = {
            'Total ROI': roi,
            'AVG Revenue, mln $': average_revenue_mln,
            'AVG Budget, mln $': average_budget_mln,
            'Category Count': category_count  # Add category count to the dictionary
        }

    # Convert the results to a DataFrame for better readability
    roi_per_category_df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(roi_per_category, orient='index').reset_index()
    roi_per_category_df.columns = [category_column, 'Total ROI', 'AVG Revenue mln$', 'AVG Budget mln$', 'Category Count']

    # Sort the DataFrame by Total ROI in descending order
    roi_per_category_df = roi_per_category_df.sort_values(by='Total ROI', ascending=False)

    return roi_per_category_df

# Define a function to categorize runtime into groups (Short, Medium and Long)
def categorize_runtime(runtime):
    if runtime <= 90:
        return 'Short'
    elif runtime <= 111:
        return 'Medium'
    else:
        return 'Long'

# Apply the function to create a new column 'runtime_group'

In [42]:
def create_boxplot(df, group_by):
    # Calculate Q1, Q3, and IQR
    Q1 = df['ROI'].quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = df['ROI'].quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1

    # Determine bounds for filtering outliers
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # Filter the DataFrame to remove outliers
    df_no_outliers = df[(df['ROI'] >= lower_bound) & (df['ROI'] <= upper_bound)]

    # Calculate mean ROI for each group
    mean_roi = df_no_outliers.groupby(group_by, observed = True)['ROI'].mean().reset_index()

    # Sort the group by mean ROI
    mean_roi_sorted = mean_roi.sort_values(by='ROI', ascending=False)
    sorted_groups = mean_roi_sorted[group_by].tolist()

    # Create the boxplot with sorted groups
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.boxplot(x=pd.Categorical(df_no_outliers[group_by], categories=sorted_groups, ordered=True), y='ROI', data=df_no_outliers)
    plt.title(f'Boxplot of ROI by {group_by} (Sorted by Mean ROI)')
    plt.xlabel(group_by)
    plt.ylabel('ROI')
    plt.xticks(rotation=90)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Conclusions¶

At the start of our analysis we wanted to shed light into the below aspects:

  1. What correlates with revenues the most: budgets, popularity, user rating or runtime?

  2. What are the characteristics of a high ROI movie? Specifically:

  • which genres have high ROI;
  • what is the best runtime (range) of movies with the highest ROI;
  • which release months of a year have the highest ROI;
  • whether ROI changed overtime or it's rather stable in relation to a release year.

Following the analysis presented above as well as looking into the correlation coefficients and plotting graphs we made the below observations:

  1. There is a relationship of Budget and Revenue, which is becoming more apparent in the latest years - ceteris paribus investing more money can eventually result in higher revenues and there is a trend of an increased importance of higher spending in the most recent years of data. One could assume that nowadays more successful movies need higher investments compared to 60s or 70s.
  2. Popularity has a positive correlation with Revenue, but the trend does not seem to be highly dependant from release year categories in the same way as for the Budget.
  3. Budget has a higher correlation with Revenue compared to Popularity, Vote average and Runtime. The latter two (Vote average and Runtime) have comparatively low correlation with Revenue and potentially need an additional analysis looking deeply into their trends as they seem to have different patterns such as accumulation around certain standard level.
  4. Based on the two different perspectives towards calculating ROI, we can see that Family and Adventure genres could be areas of an interest to an investor in the movie production industry due to it's higher ROI for the subset of movies as a whole (incl. outliers) and per movie on average. Both of them though require a certain level of Initial Investments and Budget. More detailed information of all the genres can be derived from the relevant section. In case of further interest in certain genres, an additional analysis can be performed per genre including relationship to production company, director and cast.
  5. According to the performed both metrics, Long movies seem to have higher ROI both in Total ROI terms as well as as a mean ROI per movie. Apparently, it makes sense to go extra mile in terms of increasing runtime above average.
  6. Looking into the historical data, period from May through July and November-December are the best months if an investor or a movie producer wants to release an upcoming movie to maximize ROI of their investments.
  7. Based on TMDb movie data, Return on Investment was fluctuating over various periods, with a trend towards its reduction in the recent categories of years. Meaning that ROI generally is going down compared to for example 80s and 90s.

There are several limitations and data constraints:

  • Data could potentially contain outliers (e.g. high values in popularity column) and incorrect data (e.g. zero budget and revenue), that can deteriorate the quality of insights derived from the analysis. An additional analysis, deep dives and cleaning can be performed, if required.
  • Each movie can be in several genres, which means that the total count of all the genres is higher than the total number of movies. Subsequently, there is a duplicated statistics in those cases.
  • Due to the increased number of movies (in count) overtime, the recent periods will have a bigger impact compared to earlier periods.

We hope that this Report provides you with data analysis and insights helpful in ensuring a financial success of a movie!
